# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: superconducting-materials
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] In physics, the **Bardeen–Cooper–Schrieffer** (**BCS**) **theory** is a microscopic theory of superconductivity which explains many thermodynamic and electromagnetic properties of superconductors.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] The theory describes superconductivity as a microscopic effect caused by a condensation of pairs of electrons known as Cooper pairs.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] These pairs move through the lattice without resistance.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] The theory is named after John Bardeen, Leon Cooper, and John Robert Schrieffer who proposed it in 1957 while at the University of Illinois.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] They received the Nobel Prize in Physics for this theory in 1972.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] The theory predicts many properties of superconductors such as the energy gap, the isotope effect, and the Meissner effect.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] Many superconductors can be described entirely by BCS theory and its extensions; these are called conventional superconductors.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] Unconventional superconductors, on the other hand, cannot be described by BCS theory in entirety.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] Unconventional superconductors and their relationship with BCS theory is an open research question in condensed matter physics.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] The theory is also used in nuclear physics to describe the pairing interaction between nucleons in an atomic nucleus.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] Superconductivity was first experimentally observed in 1911 by Heike Kamerlingh Onnes, for which he won the 1913 Nobel Prize.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] From the time of the discovery to the 1950s, many scientists tried to conceive of a theory for superconductivity, but initial progress was slow, as a quantum theory for metals had not been developed.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] Rapid progress in understanding superconductivity gained momentum in the 1950s.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] It began with the 1948 paper, "On the Problem of the Molecular Theory of Superconductivity", where Fritz London proposed that the phenomenological London equations may be consequences of the coherence of a quantum state.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] In 1950, Lev Landau and Vitaly Ginzburg proposed a phenomenological theory of superconductors known as Ginzburg-Landau theory, which proposed that the electrons in a superconductor acted as a charged superfluid.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] In 1953, Brian Pippard, motivated by penetration experiments, proposed a new scale parameter modifying the London equations called the coherence length.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] John Bardeen then argued in the 1955 paper, "Theory of the Meissner Effect in Superconductors", that such a modification naturally occurs in a theory with an energy gap.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] Leon Cooper calculated of the bound states of electrons subject to an attractive force in his 1956 paper, "Bound Electron Pairs in a Degenerate Fermi Gas".
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] At this time, then-graduate student Robert Schrieffer began working on superconductivity at the University of Illinois along with John Bardeen as his thesis advisor, and Leon Cooper as a postdoctoral fellow.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] In January of 1957, while attending a many-body theory meeting at the Stevens Institute of Technology, Schrieffer thought of the idea of using a statistical approach analogous to a mean field, because of the strong overlap of electron pairs in the superconductor.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] This was a breakthrough as it allowed Schrieffer to guess an appropriate ground-state wavefunction, now known as the BCS wavefunction.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] This allowed Bardeen, Cooper and Schrieffer to synthesize their ideas into a microscopic theory.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] Their theory was published in April as a letter titled "Microscopic Theory of Superconductivity".
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] The results were later published as a December 1957 paper titled "Theory of Superconductivity", which included the initial results of the letter, as well as derivations of the phase transition is second order, the Meissner effect and the calculations of specific heats and penetration depths.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] The trio received the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1972 for their theory.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] In 1986, high-temperature superconductivity was discovered in La-Ba-Cu-O, at temperatures up to 30 K.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] Following experiments determined more materials with transition temperatures up to about 130 K, considerably above the previous limit of about 30 K.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] It is experimentally very well known that the transition temperature strongly depends on pressure.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] In general, it is believed that BCS theory alone cannot explain this phenomenon and that other effects are in play.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] These effects are still not yet fully understood; it is possible that they even control superconductivity at low temperatures for some materials.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] At sufficiently low temperatures, electrons near the Fermi surface become unstable against the formation of Cooper pairs.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] Cooper showed such binding will occur in the presence of an attractive potential, no matter how weak.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] In conventional superconductors, an attraction is generally attributed to an electron-lattice interaction.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] The BCS theory, however, requires only that the potential be attractive, regardless of its origin.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] In the BCS framework, superconductivity is a macroscopic effect which results from the condensation of Cooper pairs.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] These have some bosonic properties, and bosons, at sufficiently low temperature, can form a large Bose–Einstein condensate.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] Superconductivity was simultaneously explained by Nikolay Bogolyubov, by means of the Bogoliubov transformations.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] In many superconductors, the attractive interaction between electrons (necessary for pairing) is brought about indirectly by the Bardeen–Pines interaction between the electrons and the vibrating crystal lattice (the phonons).
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] BCS theory starts from the assumption that there is some attraction between electrons, which can overcome the Coulomb repulsion.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] In most materials (in low temperature superconductors), this attraction is brought about indirectly by the coupling of electrons to the crystal lattice (as explained above).
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] However, the results of BCS theory do *not* depend on the origin of the attractive interaction.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] For instance, Cooper pairs have been observed in ultracold gases of fermions where a homogeneous magnetic field has been tuned to their Feshbach resonance.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] The original results of BCS (discussed below) described an s-wave superconducting state, which is the rule among low-temperature superconductors but is not realized in many unconventional superconductors such as the d-wave high-temperature superconductors.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] Extensions of BCS theory exist to describe these other cases, although they are insufficient to completely describe the observed features of high-temperature superconductivity.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] BCS is able to give an approximation for the quantum-mechanical many-body state of the system of (attractively interacting) electrons inside the metal.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] This state is now known as the BCS state.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] In the normal state of a metal, electrons move independently, whereas in the BCS state, they are bound into Cooper pairs by the attractive interaction.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] The BCS formalism is based on the reduced potential for the electrons' attraction.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] Within this potential, a variational ansatz for the wave function is proposed.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] This ansatz was later shown to be exact in the dense limit of pairs.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] Note that the continuous crossover between the dilute and dense regimes of attracting pairs of fermions is still an open problem, which now attracts a lot of attention within the field of ultracold gases.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] The site comments that "a drastic change in conductivity demanded a drastic change in electron behavior".
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] of phonons in a lattice is proportional to the inverse of the square root of the mass of lattice ions.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] An exponential increase in heat capacity near the critical temperature also suggests an energy bandgap for the superconducting material.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] is warmed toward its critical temperature, its heat capacity increases greatly in a very few degrees; this suggests an energy gap being bridged by thermal energy.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] exists but it is gradually weakened as the temperature increases toward the critical temperature.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] A binding energy suggests two or more particles or other entities that are bound together in the superconducting state.
[src:superconducting-materials/bcs-theory] This helped to support the idea of bound particles – specifically electron pairs – and together with the above helped to paint a general picture of paired electrons and their lattice interactions.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] In condensed matter physics, a **Cooper pair** or **BCS pair** (**Bardeen–Cooper–Schrieffer pair**) is a pair of electrons (or other fermions) bound together at low temperatures in a certain manner first described in 1956 by American physicist Leon Cooper.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] The Cooper pairing of electrons in certain materials at low temperatures is responsible for the phenomenon of superconductivity.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] Cooper showed that an arbitrarily small attraction between electrons in a metal can cause a paired state of electrons to have a lower energy than the Fermi energy, which implies that the pair is bound.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] In conventional superconductors, this attraction is due to Bardeen–Pines interaction, a type of electron–phonon interaction.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] The Cooper pair state is responsible for superconductivity, as described in the BCS theory developed by John Bardeen, Leon Cooper, and John Schrieffer for which they shared the 1972 Nobel Prize in Physics.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] Although Cooper pairing is a quantum effect, the reason for the pairing can be seen from a simplified classical explanation.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] An electron in a metal normally behaves as a free particle.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] The electron is repelled from other electrons due to their negative charge, but it also attracts the positive ions that make up the rigid lattice of the metal.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] This attraction distorts the ion lattice, moving the ions slightly toward the electron, increasing the positive charge density of the lattice in the vicinity.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] This positive charge can attract other electrons.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] At long distances, this attraction between electrons due to the displaced ions can overcome the electrons' repulsion due to their negative charge, and cause them to pair up.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] The rigorous quantum mechanical explanation shows that the effect is due to electron–phonon interactions, with the phonon being the collective motion of the positively-charged lattice.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] The energy of the pairing interaction is quite weak, of the order of 10−3 eV, and thermal energy can easily break the pairs.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] So only at low temperatures, in metal and other substrates, are a significant number of the electrons bound in Cooper pairs.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] The electrons in a pair are not necessarily close together; because the interaction is long range, paired electrons may still be many hundreds of nanometers apart.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] This distance is usually greater than the average interelectron distance so that many Cooper pairs can occupy the same space.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] Electrons have spin-1⁄2, so they are fermions, but the total spin of a Cooper pair is integer (0 or 1) so it is a composite boson.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] This means the wave functions are symmetric under particle interchange.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] Therefore, unlike electrons, multiple Cooper pairs are allowed to be in the same quantum state, which is responsible for the phenomenon of superconductivity.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] The BCS theory is also applicable to other fermion systems, such as helium-3.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] Indeed, Cooper pairing is responsible for the superfluidity of helium-3 at low temperatures.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] In 2008 it was proposed that pairs of bosons in an optical lattice may be similar to Cooper pairs.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] The tendency for all the Cooper pairs in a body to "condense" into the same ground quantum state is responsible for the peculiar properties of superconductivity.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] Cooper originally considered only the case of an isolated pair's formation in a metal.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] This *gap to excitations* leads to superconductivity, since small excitations such as scattering of electrons are forbidden.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] The gap appears due to many-body effects between electrons feeling the attraction.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] Ogg Jr., was first to suggest that electrons might act as pairs coupled by lattice vibrations in the material.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] This was indicated by the isotope effect observed in superconductors.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] The isotope effect showed that materials with heavier ions (different nuclear isotopes) had lower superconducting transition temperatures.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] This can be explained by the theory of Cooper pairing: heavier ions are harder for the electrons to attract and move (how Cooper pairs are formed), which results in smaller binding energy for the pairs.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] The theory of Cooper pairs is quite general and does not depend on the specific electron-phonon interaction.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] Condensed matter theorists have proposed pairing mechanisms based on other attractive interactions such as electron–exciton interactions or electron–plasmon interactions.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] Currently, none of these other pairing interactions has been observed in any material.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] Although the term *Cooper pairs* is commonly used, it is more accurate to speak of *Cooper pairing*, as superconductivity does not arise from individual electrons binding into localized "quasi-bosons" that would follow Bose–Einstein statistics.
[src:superconducting-materials/cooper-pair] Rather, by forming a coherent many-body ground state, electrons make optimal use of the available phase space under the Pauli exclusion principle.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The major advantage of high-temperature superconductors is that they can be cooled using liquid nitrogen, in contrast to previously known superconductors, which require expensive and hard-to-handle coolants, primarily liquid helium.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] A second advantage of high-Tc materials is they retain their superconductivity in higher magnetic fields than previous materials.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] This is important when constructing superconducting magnets, a primary application of high-Tc materials.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The majority of high-temperature superconductors are ceramics, rather than the previously known metallic materials.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Ceramic superconductors are suitable for some practical uses but encounter manufacturing issues.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] For example, most ceramics are brittle, which complicates wire fabrication.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The main class of high-temperature superconductors is copper oxides combined with other metals, especially the rare-earth barium copper oxides (REBCOs) such as yttrium barium copper oxide (YBCO).
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The second class of high-temperature superconductors in the practical classification is the iron-based compounds.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Magnesium diboride is sometimes included in high-temperature superconductors: It is relatively simple to manufacture, but it superconducts only below 39 K (−234.2 °C), which makes it unsuitable for liquid nitrogen cooling.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Superconductivity was discovered by Kamerlingh Onnes in 1911, in a metal solid.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Ever since, researchers have attempted to create superconductivity at higher temperatures with the goal of finding a room-temperature superconductor.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] By the late 1970s, superconductivity was observed in several metallic compounds (in particular Nb-based, such as NbTi, Nb3Sn, and Nb3Ge) at temperatures that were much higher than those for elemental metals and which could even exceed 20 K (−253.2 °C).
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] In 1986, at the IBM research lab near Zürich in Switzerland, Bednorz and Müller were looking for superconductivity in a new class of ceramics: the copper oxides, or cuprates.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] In that year, Bednorz and Müller discovered superconductivity in lanthanum barium copper oxide (LBCO), a lanthanum-based cuprate perovskite material, which had a transition temperature of 35 K (Nobel Prize in Physics, 1987).
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] It was soon found that replacing the lanthanum with yttrium (i.e., making YBCO) raised the critical temperature above 90 K.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Their results were soon confirmed by many groups.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Anderson gave the first theoretical description of these materials, based on the resonating valence bond (RVB) theory, but a full understanding of these materials is still developing today.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] These superconductors are now known to possess a *d*-wave pair symmetry.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The first proposal that high-temperature cuprate superconductivity involves *d*-wave pairing was made in 1987 by N.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Scalettar, followed by three subsequent theories in 1988 by Masahiko Inui, Sebastian Doniach, Peter J.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Ruckenstein, using spin-fluctuation theory, and by Claudius Gros, Didier Poilblanc, Maurice T.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Zhang, and by Gabriel Kotliar and Jialin Liu identifying *d*-wave pairing as a natural consequence of the RVB theory.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Until 2001 the cuprates were thought be the only true high temperature superconductors.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] In that year MgB2 with Tc of 39K was discovered by Akimitsu and colleagues.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] This was followed in 2006 by Hosono and coworkers with iron-based layered oxypnictide compound with Tc of 56K.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] These temperature are below the cuprates but well above the conventional superconductors.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] In 2014, evidence showing that fractional particles can happen in quasi two-dimensional magnetic materials was reported by École Polytechnique Fédérale de Lausanne (EPFL) scientists lending support for Anderson's theory of high-temperature superconductivity.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] In 2014 and 2015, hydrogen sulfide (H 2S) at extremely high pressures (around 150 gigapascals) was first predicted and then confirmed to be a high-temperature superconductor with a transition temperature of 80 K.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] In 2018, a research team from the Department of Physics, Massachusetts Institute of Technology, discovered superconductivity in bilayer graphene with one layer twisted at an angle of approximately 1.1 degrees with cooling and applying a small electric charge.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Even if the experiments were not carried out in a high-temperature environment, the results are correlated less to classical but high temperature superconductors, given that no foreign atoms needed to be introduced.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The superconductivity effect came about as a result of electrons twisted into a vortex between the graphene layers, called "skyrmions".
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] These act as a single particle and can pair up across the graphene's layers, leading to the basic conditions required for superconductivity.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] In 2019 it was discovered that lanthanum hydride (LaH 10) becomes a superconductor at 250 K under a pressure of 170 gigapascals.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] In 2020, a room-temperature superconductor (critical temperature 288 K) made from hydrogen, carbon and sulfur under pressures of around 270 gigapascals was described in a paper in *Nature*.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] However, in 2022 the article was retracted by the editors because the validity of background subtraction procedures had been called into question.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] All nine authors maintain that the raw data strongly support the main claims of the paper.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] As of 2021, the superconductor with the highest transition temperature at ambient pressure was the cuprate of mercury, barium, and calcium, at around 133 K (−140 °C).
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Other superconductors have higher recorded transition temperatures – for example lanthanum superhydride at 250 K (−23 °C), but these only occur at high pressure.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] In 2023 a study reported superconductivity at room temperature and ambient pressure in highly oriented pyrolytic graphite with dense arrays of nearly parallel line defects.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The "high-temperature" superconductor class has had many definitions.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The label high-Tc should be reserved for materials with critical temperatures greater than the boiling point of liquid nitrogen.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] However, a number of materials – including the original discovery and recently discovered pnictide superconductors – have critical temperatures below 77 K (−196.2 °C) but nonetheless are commonly referred to in publications as high-Tc class.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] A substance with a critical temperature above the boiling point of liquid nitrogen, together with a high critical magnetic field and critical current density (above which superconductivity is destroyed), would greatly benefit technological applications.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] In magnet applications, the high critical magnetic field may prove more valuable than the high Tc itself.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Some cuprates have an upper critical field of about 100 tesla.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] However, cuprate materials are brittle ceramics that are expensive to manufacture and not easily turned into wires or other useful shapes.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Furthermore, high-temperature superconductors do not form large, continuous superconducting domains, rather clusters of microdomains within which superconductivity occurs.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] They are therefore unsuitable for applications requiring actual superconductive currents, such as magnets for magnetic resonance spectrometers.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] For a solution to this (powders), see HTS wire.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] There has been considerable debate regarding high-temperature superconductivity coexisting with magnetic ordering in YBCO, iron-based superconductors, several ruthenocuprates and other exotic superconductors, and the search continues for other families of materials.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] HTS are Type-II superconductors, which allow magnetic fields to penetrate their interior in quantized units of flux, meaning that much higher magnetic fields are required to suppress superconductivity.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The layered structure also gives a directional dependence to the magnetic field response.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] All known high-Tc superconductors are Type-II superconductors.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] In contrast to Type-I superconductors, which expel all magnetic fields due to the Meissner effect, Type-II superconductors allow magnetic fields to penetrate their interior in quantized units of flux, creating "holes" or "tubes" of normal metallic regions in the superconducting bulk called vortices.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Consequently, high-Tc superconductors can sustain much higher magnetic fields.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Cuprate superconductors are a family of high-temperature superconducting materials made of layers of copper oxides (CuO 2) alternating with layers of other metal oxides, which act as charge reservoirs.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] At ambient pressure, cuprate superconductors are the highest temperature superconductors known.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Cuprates have a structure close to that of a two-dimensional material.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Their superconducting properties are determined by electrons moving within weakly coupled copper-oxide (CuO 2) layers.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Neighbouring layers contain ions such as lanthanum, barium, strontium, or other atoms that act to stabilize the structures and dope electrons or holes onto the copper-oxide layers.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The undoped "parent" or "mother" compounds are Mott insulators with long-range antiferromagnetic order at sufficiently low temperatures.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Single band models are generally considered to be enough to describe the electronic properties.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The cuprate superconductors adopt a perovskite structure.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The copper-oxide planes are checkerboard lattices with squares of O2− ions with a Cu2+ ion at the centre of each square.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The unit cell is rotated by 45° from these squares.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Chemical formulae of superconducting materials contain fractional numbers to describe the doping required for superconductivity.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Several families of cuprate superconductors have been identified.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] They can be categorized by their elements and the number of adjacent copper-oxide layers in each superconducting block.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] For example, YBCO and BSCCO can be referred to as Y123 and Bi2201/Bi2212/Bi2223 depending on the number of layers in each superconducting block (*n*).
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The superconducting transition temperature peaks at an optimal doping value (*p*=0.16) and an optimal number of layers in each block, typically three.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Possible mechanisms for cuprate superconductivity remain the subject of considerable debate and research.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Recent work on the Fermi surface has shown that nesting occurs at four points in the antiferromagnetic Brillouin zone where spin waves exist and that the superconducting energy gap is larger at these points.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The weak isotope effects observed for most cuprates contrast with conventional superconductors that are well described by BCS theory.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Iron-based superconductors contain layers of iron and a pnictogen – such as arsenic or phosphorus – , a chalcogen, or a crystallogen.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] This is currently the family with the second highest critical temperature, behind the cuprates.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Interest in their superconducting properties began in 2006 with the discovery of superconductivity in LaFePO at 4 K (−269.15 °C) and gained much greater attention in 2008 after the analogous material LaFeAs(O,F) was found to superconduct at up to 43 K (−230.2 °C) under pressure.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The highest critical temperatures in the iron-based superconductor family exist in thin films of FeSe, where a critical temperature in excess of 100 K (−173 °C) was reported in 2014.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Most undoped iron-based superconductors show a tetragonal-orthorhombic structural phase transition followed at lower temperature by magnetic ordering, similar to the cuprate superconductors.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] However, they are poor metals rather than Mott insulators and have five bands at the Fermi surface rather than one.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The phase diagram emerging as the iron-arsenide layers are doped is remarkably similar, with the superconducting phase close to or overlapping the magnetic phase.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Strong evidence that the Tc value varies with the As–Fe–As bond angles has already emerged and shows that the optimal Tc value is obtained with undistorted FeAs4 tetrahedra.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The symmetry of the pairing wavefunction is still widely debated, but an extended *s*-wave scenario is currently favoured.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Magnesium diboride is occasionally referred to as a high-temperature superconductor because its Tc value of 39 K (−234.2 °C) is above that historically expected for BCS superconductors.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] However, it is more generally regarded as the highest Tc conventional superconductor, the increased Tc resulting from two separate bands being present at the Fermi level.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] In 1991 Hebard et al. discovered Fulleride superconductors, where alkali-metal atoms are intercalated into C60 molecules.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] In 2008 Ganin et al. demonstrated superconductivity at temperatures of up to 38 K (−235.2 °C) for Cs3C60.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] P-doped Graphane was proposed in 2010 to be capable of sustaining high-temperature superconductivity.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] In 1999, Anisimov et al. conjectured superconductivity in nickelates, proposing nickel oxides as direct analogs to the cuprate superconductors.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Superconductivity in an infinite-layer nickelate, Nd0.8Sr0.2NiO2, was reported at the end of 2019 with a superconducting transition temperature between 9 and 15 K (−264.15 and −258.15 °C).
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] This superconducting phase is observed in oxygen-reduced thin films created by the pulsed laser deposition of Nd0.8Sr0.2NiO3 onto SrTiO3 substrates that is then reduced to Nd0.8Sr0.2NiO2 via annealing the thin films at 533–553 K (260–280 °C) in the presence of CaH2.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The superconducting phase is only observed in the oxygen reduced film and is not seen in oxygen reduced bulk material of the same stoichiometry, suggesting that the strain induced by the oxygen reduction of the Nd0.8Sr0.2NiO2 thin film changes the phase space to allow for superconductivity.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Of important is further to extract access hydrogen from the reduction with CaH2, otherwise topotactic hydrogen may prevent superconductivity.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Liquid nitrogen can be produced relatively cheaply, even on-site.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The higher temperatures additionally help to avoid some of the problems that arise at liquid helium temperatures, such as the formation of plugs of frozen air that can block cryogenic lines and cause unanticipated and potentially hazardous pressure buildup.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The question of how superconductivity arises in high-temperature superconductors is one of the major unsolved problems of theoretical condensed matter physics.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The mechanism that causes the electrons in these crystals to form pairs is not known.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Despite intensive research and many promising leads, an explanation has so far eluded scientists.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] One reason for this is that the materials in question are generally very complex, multi-layered crystals (for example, BSCCO), making theoretical modelling difficult.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Improving the quality and variety of samples also gives rise to considerable research, both with the aim of improved characterisation of the physical properties of existing compounds, and synthesizing new materials, often with the hope of increasing Tc.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Technological research focuses on making HTS materials in sufficient quantities to make their use economically viable as well as in optimizing their properties in relation to applications.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] In March 2026, University of Houston researchers reported a superconducting material exhibiting a critical temperature of approximately 151 K at ambient pressure.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] This new record without sustained high-pressure conditions was achieved using a "pressure quenching" technique.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] This exceeded the previous ambient-pressure record of 133 K.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Multiple hypotheses attempt to account for HTS.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Spin fluctuation hypothesis proposed that electron pairing in high-temperature superconductors is mediated by short-range spin waves known as paramagnons.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Gubser, Hartnoll, Herzog, and Horowitz proposed holographic superconductivity, which uses holographic duality or AdS/CFT correspondence theory as a possible explanation of high-temperature superconductivity in certain materials.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Weak coupling theory suggests superconductivity emerges from antiferromagnetic spin fluctuations in a doped system.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] It predicts that the pairing wave function of cuprate HTS should have a *d*x2-y2 symmetry.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Thus, determining whether the pairing wave function has *d*-wave symmetry is essential to test the spin fluctuation mechanism.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] That is, if the HTS order parameter (a pairing wave function as in Ginzburg–Landau theory) does not have *d*-wave symmetry, then a pairing mechanism related to spin fluctuations can be ruled out.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Interlayer coupling theory proposes that a layered structure consisting of BCS-type (*s*-wave symmetry) superconductors can explain superconductivity by itself.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] By introducing an additional tunnelling interaction between layers, this model explained the anisotropic symmetry of the order parameter as well as the emergence of HTS.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] In order to resolve this question, experiments such as photoemission spectroscopy, NMR, specific heat measurements, were conducted.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The results remain ambiguous, with some reports supporting *d* symmetry, with others supporting *s* symmetry.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Such explanations assume that superconductive properties can be treated by mean-field theory.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] It also does not consider that in addition to the superconductive gap, the pseudogap must be explained.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The cuprate layers are insulating, and the superconductors are doped with interlayer impurities to make them metallic.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The transition temperature can be maximized by varying the dopant concentration.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The simplest example is La2CuO4, which consists of alternating CuO2 and LaO layers that are insulating when pure.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] When 8% of the La is replaced by Sr, the latter acts as a dopant, contributing holes to the CuO2 layers, and making the sample metallic.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The Sr impurities also act as electronic bridges, enabling interlayer coupling.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Proceeding from this picture, some theories argue that the pairing interaction is with phonons, as in conventional superconductors with Cooper pairs.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] While the undoped materials are antiferromagnetic, even a few percent of impurity dopants introduce a smaller pseudogap in the CuO2 planes that is also caused by phonons.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The gap decreases with increasing charge carriers, and as it nears the superconductive gap, the latter reaches its maximum.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The transition temperature maxima are reached when the host lattice has weak bond-bending forces, which produce strong electron–phonon interactions at the interlayer dopants.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] An experiment based on flux quantization of a three-grain ring of YBa2Cu3O7 (YBCO) was proposed to test the symmetry of the order parameter in the HTS.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The symmetry of the order parameter could best be probed at the junction interface as the Cooper pairs tunnel across a Josephson junction or weak link.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] It was expected that a half-integer flux, that is, a spontaneous magnetization could only occur for a junction of *d* symmetry superconductors.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] But, even if the junction experiment is the strongest method to determine the symmetry of the HTS order parameter, the results have been ambiguous.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Tsuei thought that the ambiguous results came from the defects inside the HTS, leading them to an experiment where both clean limit (no defects) and dirty limit (maximal defects) were considered simultaneously.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Spontaneous magnetization was clearly observed in YBCO, which supported the *d* symmetry of the order parameter in YBCO.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] But, since YBCO is orthorhombic, it might inherently have an admixture of *s* symmetry.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] By tuning their technique, they found an admixture of *s* symmetry in YBCO within about 3%.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Also, they found a pure *d*x2−y2 order parameter symmetry in tetragonal Tl2Ba2CuO6.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] The lack of exact theoretical computations on such strongly interacting electron systems has complicated attempts to validate spin-fluctuation.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] However, most theoretical calculations, including phenomenological and diagrammatic approaches, converge on magnetic fluctuations as the pairing mechanism.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] In a superconductor, the flow of electrons cannot be resolved into individual electrons, but instead consists of pairs of bound electrons, called Cooper pairs.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] In conventional superconductors, these pairs are formed when an electron moving through the material distorts the surrounding crystal lattice, which attracts another electron and forms a bound pair.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] This is sometimes called the "water bed" effect.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Each Cooper pair requires a certain minimum energy to be displaced, and if the thermal fluctuations in the crystal lattice are smaller than this energy the pair can flow without dissipating energy.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Electron flow without resistance is superconductivity.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] In a high-Tc superconductor, the mechanism is extremely similar to a conventional superconductor, except that phonons play virtually no role, replaced by spin-density waves.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Just as all known conventional superconductors are strong phonon systems, all known high-Tc superconductors are strong spin-density wave systems, within close vicinity of a magnetic transition to, for example, an antiferromagnet.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] When an electron moves in a high-Tc superconductor, its spin creates a spin-density wave around it.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] This spin-density wave in turn causes a nearby electron to fall into the spin depression created by the first electron (water-bed).
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] When the system temperature is lowered, more spin density waves and Cooper pairs are created, eventually leading to superconductivity.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] High-Tc systems are magnetic systems due to the Coulomb interaction, creating a strong Coulomb repulsion between electrons.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] This repulsion prevents pairing of the Cooper pairs on the same lattice site.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Instead, pairing occurs at near-neighbor lattice sites.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] This is the so-called *d*-wave pairing, where the pairing state has a node (zero) at the origin.
[src:superconducting-materials/high-temperature-superconductivity] Examples of high-Tc cuprate superconductors include YBCO and BSCCO, which are the most known materials that achieve superconductivity above the boiling point of liquid nitrogen.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] In condensed-matter physics, the **Meissner effect** (or **Meissner–Ochsenfeld effect**) is the expulsion of a magnetic field from a superconductor during its transition to the superconducting state when it is cooled below the critical temperature.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] This expulsion will repel a nearby magnet.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] The German physicists Walther Meissner and Robert Ochsenfeld discovered this phenomenon in 1933 by measuring the magnetic field distribution outside superconducting tin and lead samples.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] The samples, in the presence of an applied magnetic field, were cooled below their superconducting transition temperature, whereupon the samples cancelled nearly all interior magnetic fields.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] They detected this effect only indirectly because the magnetic flux is conserved by a superconductor: when the interior field decreases, the exterior field increases.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] The experiment demonstrated for the first time that superconductors were more than just perfect conductors and provided a uniquely defining property of the superconductor state.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] The ability for the expulsion effect is determined by the nature of equilibrium formed by the neutralization within the unit cell of a superconductor.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] where **H** is the magnetic field and λ is the London penetration depth.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] This equation, known as the London equation, predicts that the magnetic field in a superconductor decays exponentially from whatever value it possesses at the surface.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] This exclusion of magnetic field is a manifestation of the superdiamagnetism which emerges during the phase transition from conductor to superconductor, for example by reducing the temperature below critical temperature.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] These surface currents shield the internal bulk of the superconductor from the external applied field.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] As the field expulsion, or cancellation, does not change with time, the currents producing this effect (called persistent currents or screening currents) do not decay with time.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] Near the surface, within the London penetration depth, the magnetic field is not completely canceled.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] Each superconducting material has its own characteristic penetration depth.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] Any perfect conductor will prevent any change to magnetic flux passing through its surface due to ordinary electromagnetic induction at zero resistance.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] However, the Meissner effect is distinct from this: when an ordinary conductor is cooled so that it makes the transition to a superconducting state in the presence of a constant applied magnetic field, the magnetic flux is expelled during the transition.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] This effect cannot be explained by infinite conductivity, but only by the London equation.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] The placement and subsequent levitation of a magnet above an already superconducting material does not demonstrate the Meissner effect, while an initially stationary magnet later being repelled by a superconductor as it is cooled below its critical temperature does.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] The persisting currents that exist in the superconductor to expel the magnetic field is commonly misconceived as a result of Lenz's Law or Faraday's Law.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] A reason this is not the case is that no change in flux was made to induce the current.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] Another explanation is that since the superconductor experiences zero resistance, there cannot be an induced emf in the superconductor.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] The persisting current therefore is not a result of Faraday's Law.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] Superconductors in the Meissner state exhibit perfect diamagnetism, or superdiamagnetism, meaning that the total magnetic field is very close to zero deep inside them (many penetration depths from the surface).
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] This means that their volume magnetic susceptibility is $\chi _{v}$ = −1.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] Diamagnetics are defined by the generation of a spontaneous magnetization of a material which directly opposes the direction of an applied field.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] However, the fundamental origins of diamagnetism in superconductors and normal materials are very different.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] In normal materials diamagnetism arises as a direct result of the orbital spin of electrons about the nuclei of an atom induced electromagnetically by the application of an applied field.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] In superconductors the illusion of perfect diamagnetism arises from persistent screening currents which flow to oppose the applied field (the Meissner effect); not solely the orbital spin.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] The discovery of the Meissner effect led to the phenomenological theory of superconductivity by Fritz and Heinz London in 1935.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] This theory explained resistanceless transport and the Meissner effect, and allowed the first theoretical predictions for superconductivity to be made.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] However, this theory only explained experimental observations—it did not allow the microscopic origins of the superconducting properties to be identified.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] This was done successfully by the BCS theory in 1957, from which the penetration depth and the Meissner effect result.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] However, some physicists argue that BCS theory does not explain the Meissner effect.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] The Meissner superconductivity effect serves as an important paradigm for the generation mechanism of a mass *M* (i.e., a reciprocal *range*, $\lambda _{M}:=h/(Mc)$ where *h* is the Planck constant and *c* is the speed of light) for a gauge field.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] In fact, this analogy is an abelian example for the Higgs mechanism, which generates the masses of the electroweak W± and Z gauge particles in high-energy physics.
[src:superconducting-materials/meissner-effect] The length $\lambda _{M}$ is identical with the London penetration depth in the theory of superconductivity.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The superconductivity phenomenon was discovered in 1911 by Dutch physicist Heike Kamerlingh Onnes.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Like ferromagnetism and atomic spectral lines, superconductivity is a phenomenon which can only be explained by quantum mechanics.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] It is characterized by the Meissner effect, the complete cancellation of the magnetic field in the interior of the superconductor during its transitions into the superconducting state.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The occurrence of the Meissner effect indicates that superconductivity cannot be understood simply as the idealization of *perfect conductivity* in classical physics.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] In 1986, it was discovered that some cuprate-perovskite ceramic materials have a critical temperature above 35 K (−238 °C).
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] It was found shortly thereafter (by Ching-Wu Chu) that replacing the lanthanum with yttrium, i.e. making YBCO, raised the critical temperature to 92 K (−181 °C), which was important because liquid nitrogen could then be used as a refrigerant.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Such a high transition temperature is theoretically impossible for a conventional superconductor, leading the materials to be termed high-temperature superconductors.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The cheaply available coolant liquid nitrogen boils at 77 K (−196 °C) and thus the existence of superconductivity at higher temperatures than this facilitates many experiments and applications that are less practical at lower temperatures.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Superconductivity was discovered in solid mercury on April 8, 1911, by Heike Kamerlingh Onnes, who was studying the resistance of mercury at cryogenic temperatures using the recently produced liquid helium as a refrigerant.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] At the temperature of 4.2 K, he observed that the resistance abruptly disappeared.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] In the same experiment, he also observed the superfluid transition of helium at 2.2 K, without recognizing its significance.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The precise date and circumstances of the discovery were only reconstructed a century later, when Onnes's notebook was found.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] In subsequent decades, superconductivity was observed in several other materials.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] In 1913, Tin and lead were found to superconduct at 3.8K and 7 K respectively, and in 1941 niobium nitride was found to superconduct at 16 K.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Great efforts have been devoted to finding out how and why superconductivity works; the important step occurred in 1933, when Meissner and Ochsenfeld discovered that superconductors expelled applied magnetic fields, a phenomenon which has come to be known as the Meissner effect.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] In 1935, Fritz and Heinz London showed that the Meissner effect was a consequence of the minimization of the electromagnetic free energy carried by superconducting current.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The theoretical model that was first conceived for superconductivity was completely classical: it is summarized by London constitutive equations.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] It was put forward by the brothers Fritz and Heinz London in 1935, shortly after the discovery that magnetic fields are expelled from superconductors.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] A major triumph of the equations of this theory is their ability to explain the Meissner effect, wherein a material exponentially expels all internal magnetic fields as it crosses the superconducting threshold.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] By using the London equation, one can obtain the dependence of the magnetic field inside the superconductor on the distance to the surface.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The first equation follows from Newton's second law for superconducting electrons.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] During the 1950s, theoretical condensed matter physicists arrived at an understanding of "conventional" superconductivity, through a pair of remarkable and important theories: the phenomenological Ginzburg–Landau theory (1950) and the microscopic BCS theory (1957).
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] In 1950, the phenomenological Ginzburg–Landau theory of superconductivity was devised by Landau and Ginzburg.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] This theory, which combined Landau's theory of second-order phase transitions with a Schrödinger-like wave equation, had great success in explaining the macroscopic properties of superconductors.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] In particular, Abrikosov showed that Ginzburg–Landau theory predicts the division of superconductors into the two categories now referred to as Type I and Type II.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Abrikosov and Ginzburg were awarded the 2003 Nobel Prize for their work (Landau had received the 1962 Nobel Prize for other work, and died in 1968).
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The four-dimensional extension of the Ginzburg–Landau theory, the Coleman-Weinberg model, is important in quantum field theory and cosmology.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Also in 1950, Maxwell and Reynolds et al. found that the critical temperature of a superconductor depends on the isotopic mass of the constituent element.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] This important discovery pointed to the electron–phonon interaction as the microscopic mechanism responsible for superconductivity.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The complete microscopic theory of superconductivity was finally proposed in 1957 by Bardeen, Cooper and Schrieffer.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] This BCS theory explained the superconducting current as a superfluid of Cooper pairs, pairs of electrons interacting through the exchange of phonons.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] For this work, the authors were awarded the Nobel Prize in 1972.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The BCS theory was set on a firmer footing in 1958, when N.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Bogolyubov showed that the BCS wavefunction, which had originally been derived from a variational argument, could be obtained using a canonical transformation of the electronic Hamiltonian.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] In 1959, Lev Gor'kov showed that the BCS theory reduced to the Ginzburg–Landau theory close to the critical temperature.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Generalizations of BCS theory for conventional superconductors form the basis for the understanding of the phenomenon of superfluidity, because they fall into the lambda transition universality class.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The extent to which such generalizations can be applied to unconventional superconductors is still controversial.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The first practical application of superconductivity was developed in 1954 with Dudley Allen Buck's invention of the cryotron.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Two superconductors with greatly different values of the critical magnetic field are combined to produce a fast, simple switch for computer elements.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Soon after discovering superconductivity in 1911, Kamerlingh Onnes attempted to make an electromagnet with superconducting windings but found that relatively low magnetic fields destroyed superconductivity in the materials he investigated.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Yntema succeeded in constructing a small 0.7-tesla iron-core electromagnet with superconducting niobium wire windings.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Wernick made the startling discovery that, at 4.2 kelvin, niobium–tin, a compound consisting of three parts niobium and one part tin, was capable of supporting a current density of more than 100,000 amperes per square centimeter in a magnetic field of 8.8 tesla.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The alloy was brittle and difficult to fabricate, but niobium–tin proved useful for generating magnetic fields as high as 20 tesla.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Hake discovered that more ductile alloys of niobium and titanium are suitable for applications up to 10 tesla.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Commercial production of niobium–titanium supermagnet wire immediately commenced at Westinghouse Electric Corporation and at Wah Chang Corporation.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Although niobium–titanium boasts less-impressive superconducting properties than those of niobium–tin, niobium–titanium became the most widely used "workhorse" supermagnet material, in large measure a consequence of its very high ductility and ease of fabrication.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] However, both niobium–tin and niobium–titanium found wide application in MRI medical imagers, bending and focusing magnets for enormous high-energy-particle accelerators, and other applications.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Conectus, a European superconductivity consortium, estimated that in 2014, global economic activity for which superconductivity was indispensable amounted to about five billion euros, with MRI systems accounting for about 80% of that total.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] In 1962, Josephson made the important theoretical prediction that a supercurrent can flow between two pieces of superconductor separated by a thin layer of insulator.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] This phenomenon, now called the Josephson effect, is exploited by superconducting devices such as SQUIDs.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] It is used in the most accurate available measurements of the magnetic flux quantum *Φ*0 = *h*/(2*e*), where *h* is the Planck constant.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Coupled with the quantum Hall resistivity, this leads to a precise measurement of the Planck constant.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Josephson was awarded the Nobel Prize for this work in 1973.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] In 2008, it was proposed that the same mechanism that produces superconductivity could produce a superinsulator state in some materials, with almost infinite electrical resistance.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The first development and study of superconducting Bose–Einstein condensate (BEC) in 2020 suggested a "smooth transition between" BEC and Bardeen-Cooper-Shrieffer regimes.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Multiple types of superconductivity are reported in devices made of single-layer materials.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Some of these materials can switch between conducting, insulating, and other behaviors.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Twisting materials imbues them with a "moiré" pattern involving tiled hexagonal cells that act like atoms and host electrons.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] In this environment, the electrons move slowly enough for their collective interactions to guide their behavior.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] When each cell has a single electron, the electrons take on an antiferromagnetic arrangement; each electron can have a preferred location and magnetic orientation.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Their intrinsic magnetic fields tend to alternate between pointing up and down.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Adding electrons allows superconductivity by causing Cooper pairs to form.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Fu and Schrade argued that electron-on-electron action was allowing both antiferromagnetic and superconducting states.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The first success with 2D materials involved a twisted bilayer graphene sheet (2018, Tc ~1.7 K, 1.1° twist).
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] A twisted three-layer graphene device was later shown to superconduct (2021, Tc ~2.8 K).
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Then an untwisted trilayer graphene device was reported to superconduct (2022, Tc 1-2 K).
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The latter was later shown to be tunable, easily reproducing behavior found in millions of other configurations.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Directly observing what happens when electrons are added to a material or slightly weakening its electric field enables quick testing of an unprecedented number of recipes to see which lead to superconductivity.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] In four and five layer rhombohedral graphene, a form of superconductivity with spontaneously broken time reversal symmetry known as "chiral superconductivity" was recently observed.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] These systems were not observed to have any superlattice effects, and they can flip between two possible magnetic states without exiting the superconducting phase.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] This is in strong contrast to other observations of superconductivity and magnetic fields.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] These devices have applications in quantum computing.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] 2D materials other than graphene have also been made to superconduct.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Transition metal dichalcogenide (TMD) sheets twisted at 5 degrees intermittently achieved superconduction by creating a Josephson junction.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The device used thin layers of palladium to connect to the sides of a tungsten telluride layer surrounded and protected by boron nitride.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Another group demonstrated superconduction in molybdenum telluride (MoTe₂) in 2D van der Waals materials using ferroelectric domain walls.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The Tc was implied to be higher than typical TMDs (~5–10 K).
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] A Cornell group added a 3.5-degree twist to an insulator that allowed electrons to slow down and interact strongly, leaving one electron per cell, exhibiting superconduction.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Existing theories do not explain this behavior.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Fu and collaborators proposed that electrons arrange to form a repeating crystal that allows the electron grid to float independently of the background atomic nuclei and the electron grid to relax.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Its ripples pair electrons the way phonons do, although this is unconfirmed.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Superconductors are classified according to many criteria.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Furthermore, in multicomponent superconductors it is possible to combine the two behaviours.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] In that case the superconductor is of Type-1.5.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] A superconductor is *conventional* if it is driven by electron–phonon interaction and explained by the BCS theory or its extension, the Eliashberg theory.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Alternatively, a superconductor is called unconventional if the superconducting order parameter transforms according to a non-trivial irreducible representation of the system's point group or space group.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] A superconductor is generally considered *high-temperature* if it reaches a superconducting state above a temperature of 30 K (−243.15 °C); as in the initial discovery by Georg Bednorz and K.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] It may also reference materials that transition to superconductivity when cooled using liquid nitrogen – that is, at only *T*c > 77 K, although this is generally used only to emphasize that liquid nitrogen coolant is sufficient.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Low temperature superconductors refer to materials with a critical temperature below 30 K, and are cooled mainly by liquid helium (*T*c > 4.2 K).
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] One exception to this rule is the iron pnictide group of superconductors that display behaviour and properties typical of high-temperature superconductors, yet some of the group have critical temperatures below 30 K.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Several physical properties of superconductors vary from material to material, such as the critical temperature, the value of the superconducting gap, the critical magnetic field, and the critical current density at which superconductivity is destroyed.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] On the other hand, there is a class of properties that are independent of the underlying material.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The Meissner effect, the quantization of the magnetic flux or permanent currents, i.e. the state of zero resistance are the most important examples.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The existence of these "universal" properties is rooted in the nature of the broken symmetry of the superconductor and the emergence of off-diagonal long range order.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Superconductivity is a thermodynamic phase, and thus possesses certain distinguishing properties which are largely independent of microscopic details.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Off diagonal long range order is closely connected to the formation of Cooper pairs.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The simplest method to measure the electrical resistance of a sample of some material is to place it in an electrical circuit in series with a current source *I* and measure the resulting voltage *V* across the sample.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The resistance of the sample is given by Ohm's law as *R = V / I*.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] If the voltage drop across the sample is zero, this means that the resistance is zero.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Superconductors are also able to maintain a current with no applied voltage whatsoever, a property exploited in superconducting electromagnets such as those found in MRI machines.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Experiments have demonstrated that currents in superconducting coils can persist for years without any measurable degradation.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Experimental evidence points to a lifetime of at least 100,000 years.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Theoretical estimates for the lifetime of a persistent current can exceed the estimated lifetime of the universe, depending on the wire geometry and the temperature.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] In practice, currents injected in superconducting coils persisted for 28 years, 7 months, 27 days in a superconducting gravimeter in Belgium, from August 4, 1995 until March 31, 2024.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] In such instruments, the measurement is based on the monitoring of the levitation of a superconducting niobium sphere with a mass of four grams.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] In a normal conductor, an electric current may be visualized as a fluid of electrons moving across a heavy ionic lattice.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The electrons are constantly colliding with the ions in the lattice, and during each collision some of the energy carried by the current is absorbed by the lattice and converted into heat, which is essentially the vibrational kinetic energy of the lattice ions.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] As a result, the energy carried by the current is constantly being dissipated.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] This is the phenomenon of electrical resistance and Joule heating.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The situation is different in a superconductor.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] In a conventional superconductor, the electronic fluid cannot be resolved into individual electrons.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Instead, it consists of bound *pairs* of electrons known as Cooper pairs.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] This pairing is caused by an attractive force between electrons from the exchange of phonons.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] This pairing is very weak, and small thermal vibrations can fracture the bond.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Due to quantum mechanics, the energy spectrum of this Cooper pair fluid possesses an *energy gap*, meaning there is a minimum amount of energy Δ*E* that must be supplied in order to excite the fluid.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Therefore, if Δ*E* is larger than the thermal energy of the lattice, given by *kT*, where *k* is the Boltzmann constant and *T* is the temperature, the fluid will not be scattered by the lattice.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The Cooper pair fluid is thus a superfluid, meaning it can flow without energy dissipation.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] This is due to the motion of magnetic vortices in the electronic superfluid, which dissipates some of the energy carried by the current.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] If the current is sufficiently small, the vortices are stationary, and the resistivity vanishes.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The resistance due to this effect is minuscule compared with that of non-superconducting materials, but must be taken into account in sensitive experiments.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] However, as the temperature decreases far enough below the nominal superconducting transition, these vortices can become frozen into a disordered but stationary phase known as a "vortex glass".
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Below this vortex glass transition temperature, the resistance of the material becomes truly zero.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] In superconducting materials, the characteristics of superconductivity appear when the temperature *T* is lowered below a critical temperature *T*c.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The value of this critical temperature varies from material to material.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Conventional superconductors usually have critical temperatures ranging from around 20 K to less than 1 K.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Solid mercury, for example, has a critical temperature of 4.2 K.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] As of 2015, the highest critical temperature found for a conventional superconductor is 203 K for H2S, although high pressures of approximately 90 gigapascals were required.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Cuprate superconductors can have much higher critical temperatures: YBa2Cu3O7, one of the first cuprate superconductors to be discovered, has a critical temperature above 90 K, and mercury-based cuprates have been found with critical temperatures in excess of 130 K.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The basic physical mechanism responsible for the high critical temperature is not yet clear.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] However, it is clear that a two-electron pairing is involved, although the nature of the pairing ( s wave vs. d wave) remains controversial.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Similarly, at a fixed temperature below the critical temperature, superconducting materials cease to superconduct when an external magnetic field is applied which is greater than the *critical magnetic field*.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] This is because the Gibbs free energy of the superconducting phase increases quadratically with the magnetic field while the free energy of the normal phase is roughly independent of the magnetic field.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] More generally, a higher temperature and a stronger magnetic field lead to a smaller fraction of electrons that are superconducting and consequently to a longer London penetration depth of external magnetic fields and currents.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The penetration depth becomes infinite at the phase transition.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The onset of superconductivity is accompanied by abrupt changes in various physical properties, which is the hallmark of a phase transition.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] For example, the electronic heat capacity is proportional to the temperature in the normal (non-superconducting) regime.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] At the superconducting transition, it suffers a discontinuous jump and thereafter ceases to be linear.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] At low temperatures, it varies instead as *e*−*α*/*T* for some constant, *α*.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] This exponential behavior is one of the pieces of evidence for the existence of the energy gap.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The order of the superconducting phase transition was long a matter of debate.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Experiments indicate that the transition is second-order, meaning there is no latent heat.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] However, in the presence of an external magnetic field there is latent heat, because the superconducting phase has a lower entropy below the critical temperature than the normal phase.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] It has been experimentally demonstrated that, as a consequence, when the magnetic field is increased beyond the critical field, the resulting phase transition leads to a decrease in the temperature of the superconducting material.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Calculations in the 1970s suggested that it may actually be weakly first-order due to the effect of long-range fluctuations in the electromagnetic field.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The results were strongly supported by Monte Carlo computer simulations.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] When a superconductor is placed in a weak external magnetic field *B*a=*H*a, and cooled below its transition temperature, the magnetic field is ejected.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The Meissner effect does not cause the field to be completely ejected but instead, the field penetrates the superconductor but only to a very small distance, characterized by a parameter *λ*, called the London penetration depth, decaying exponentially to zero within the bulk of the material.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The Meissner effect is a defining characteristic of superconductivity.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] For most superconductors, the London penetration depth is on the order of 100 nm.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] In a perfect conductor, an arbitrarily large current can be induced, and the resulting magnetic field exactly cancels the applied field.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The Meissner effect is distinct from this – it is the spontaneous expulsion that occurs during transition to superconductivity.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Suppose we have a material in its normal state, containing a constant internal magnetic field.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] When the material is cooled below the critical temperature, we would observe the abrupt expulsion of the internal magnetic field, which we would not expect based on Lenz's law.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] This equation, which is known as the London equation, predicts that the magnetic field in a superconductor decays exponentially from whatever value it possesses at the surface.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] A superconductor with little or no magnetic field within it is said to be in the Meissner state.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The Meissner state breaks down when the applied magnetic field is too large.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Superconductors can be divided into two classes according to how this breakdown occurs.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] In Type I superconductors, superconductivity is abruptly destroyed when the strength of the applied field rises above a critical value *H*c.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Depending on the geometry of the sample, one may obtain an intermediate state consisting of a baroque pattern of regions of normal material carrying a magnetic field mixed with regions of superconducting material containing no field.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] At a second critical field strength *H*c2, superconductivity is destroyed.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The mixed state is actually caused by vortices in the electronic superfluid, sometimes called fluxons because the flux carried by these vortices is quantized.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Most pure elemental superconductors, except niobium and carbon nanotubes, are Type I, while almost all impure and compound superconductors are Type II.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Conversely, a spinning superconductor generates a magnetic field, precisely aligned with the spin axis.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The effect, the London moment, was put to good use in Gravity Probe B.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] This experiment measured the magnetic fields of four superconducting gyroscopes to determine their spin axes.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] This was critical to the experiment since it is one of the few ways to accurately determine the spin axis of an otherwise featureless sphere.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] High-temperature superconductivity (high-Tc or HTS) is superconductivity in materials with a critical temperature (the temperature below which the material behaves as a superconductor) above 77 K (−196.2 °C; −321.1 °F), the boiling point of liquid nitrogen.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] They are "high-temperature" only relative to previously known superconductors, which function only closer to absolute zero.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The first high-temperature superconductor was discovered in 1986 by IBM researchers Georg Bednorz and K.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Although the critical temperature is around 35.1 K (−238.1 °C; −396.5 °F), this material was modified by Ching-Wu Chu to make the first high-temperature superconductor with critical temperature 93 K (−180.2 °C; −292.3 °F).
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Bednorz and Müller were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1987 "for their important break-through in the discovery of superconductivity in ceramic materials".
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Most high-Tc materials are type-II superconductors.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Superconductors are promising candidate materials for devising fundamental circuit elements of electronic, spintronic, and quantum technologies.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] One such example is a superconducting diode, in which supercurrent flows along one direction only, that promise dissipationless superconducting and semiconducting-superconducting hybrid technologies.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Superconducting magnets are some of the most powerful electromagnets known.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] They are used in MRI/NMR machines, mass spectrometers, the beam-steering magnets used in particle accelerators and plasma confining magnets in some tokamaks.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] They can also be used for magnetic separation, where weakly magnetic particles are extracted from a background of less or non-magnetic particles, as in the pigment industries.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] They can also be used in large wind turbines to overcome the restrictions imposed by high electrical currents, with an industrial grade 3.6 megawatt superconducting windmill generator having been tested successfully in Denmark.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] In the 1950s and 1960s, superconductors were used to build experimental digital computers using cryotron switches.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] More recently, superconductors have been used to make digital circuits based on rapid single flux quantum technology and RF and microwave filters for mobile phone base stations.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Superconductors are used to build Josephson junctions which are the building blocks of SQUIDs (superconducting quantum interference devices), the most sensitive magnetometers known.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] SQUIDs are used in scanning SQUID microscopes and magnetoencephalography.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Series of Josephson devices are used to realize the SI volt.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Superconducting photon detectors can be realised in a variety of device configurations.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Depending on the particular mode of operation, a superconductor–insulator–superconductor Josephson junction can be used as a photon detector or as a mixer.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The large resistance change at the transition from the normal to the superconducting state is used to build thermometers in cryogenic micro-calorimeter photon detectors.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] The same effect is used in ultrasensitive bolometers made from superconducting materials.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Superconducting nanowire single-photon detectors offer high speed, low noise single-photon detection and have been employed widely in advanced photon-counting applications.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Other early markets are arising where the relative efficiency, size and weight advantages of devices based on high-temperature superconductivity outweigh the additional costs involved.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] For example, in wind turbines the lower weight and volume of superconducting generators could lead to savings in construction and tower costs, offsetting the higher costs for the generator and lowering the total levelized cost of electricity (LCOE).
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] However, superconductivity is sensitive to moving magnetic fields, so applications that use alternating current (e.g. transformers) will be more difficult to develop than those that rely upon direct current.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Compared to traditional power lines, superconducting transmission lines are more efficient and require only a fraction of the space, which would not only lead to a better environmental performance but could also improve public acceptance for expansion of the electric grid.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Another attractive industrial aspect is the ability for high power transmission at lower voltages.
[src:superconducting-materials/superconductivity] Advancements in the efficiency of cooling systems and use of cheap coolants such as liquid nitrogen have also significantly decreased cooling costs needed for superconductivity.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] In superconductivity, a **type-II superconductor** is a superconductor that exhibits an intermediate phase of mixed ordinary and superconducting properties at intermediate temperature and fields above the superconducting phases.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] It also features the formation of magnetic field vortices with an applied external magnetic field.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] This occurs above a certain critical field strength *Hc1*.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] The vortex density increases with increasing field strength.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] At a higher critical field *Hc2*, typically of the order of tens of teslas superconductivity is destroyed.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] Type-II superconductors do not exhibit a complete Meissner effect.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] The existence of two critical fields in superconducting alloys was experimentally observed by Wander Johannes De Haas and J.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] Voogd in 1929–1931, and confirmed by multiple authors working with different materials over the following years.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] However, the sample inhomogeneities in these early studies were poorly controlled, and it was assumed that the effect might be explained by structural inhomogenuities which would lead to a formation of a thin filamentary superconducting network.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] In 1936, Lev Shubnikov, Vladimir Khotkevich, Georgy Shepelev and Yuri Rjabinin produced high-quality single-crystal samples and concluded that the effect was a bulk phenomenon, ruling out structural inhomogeneity as the cause.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] The following year, Shubnikov was executed during Stalin's purges and his results remained largely unknown for the next 25 years.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] In 1950, the theory of the two types of superconductors was developed by Lev Landau and Vitaly Ginzburg in their paper on Ginzburg–Landau theory.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] In their argument, a type-I superconductor had positive free energy of the superconductor-normal metal boundary.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] Ginzburg and Landau pointed out the possibility of type-II superconductors that should form inhomogeneous state in strong magnetic fields.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] However, at that time, all known superconductors were type-I, and they commented that there was no experimental motivation to consider precise structure of type-II superconducting state.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] The theory for the behavior of the type-II superconducting state in magnetic field was greatly improved by Alexei Alexeyevich Abrikosov, who was elaborating on the ideas by Lars Onsager and Richard Feynman of quantum vortices in superfluids.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] Abrikosov compared his vortex lattice theory to Shubnikov's 1936 experiments and found a good fit.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] Quantum vortex solution in a superconductor is also very closely related to Fritz London's work on magnetic flux quantization in superconductors.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] The Nobel Prize in Physics was awarded for the theory of type-II superconductivity in 2003.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] Ginzburg–Landau theory introduced the superconducting coherence length ξ in addition to London magnetic field penetration depth λ.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] According to Ginzburg–Landau theory, in a type-II superconductor $\lambda /\xi >1/{\sqrt {2}}$ .
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] Ginzburg and Landau showed that this leads to negative energy of the interface between superconducting and normal phases.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] The existence of the negative interface energy was also known since the mid-1930s from the early works by the London brothers.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] A negative interface energy suggests that the system should be unstable against maximizing the number of such interfaces.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] This instability was not observed until the experiments of Shubnikov in 1936 where two critical fields were found.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] In 1952 an observation of type-II superconductivity was also reported by Zavaritskii.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] Fritz London demonstrated that a magnetic flux can penetrate a superconductor via a topological defect that has integer phase winding and carries quantized magnetic flux.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] Onsager and Feynman demonstrated that quantum vortices should form in superfluids.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] In the limit of very short coherence length the vortex solution is identical to London's fluxoid, where the vortex core is approximated by a sharp cutoff rather than a gradual vanishing of superconducting condensate near the vortex center.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] Abrikosov found that the vortices arrange themselves into a regular array known as a *vortex lattice*.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] Near a so-called upper critical magnetic field, the problem of a superconductor in an external field is equivalent to the problem of vortex state in a rotating superfluid, discussed by Lars Onsager and Richard Feynman.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] In the vortex state, a phenomenon known as flux pinning becomes possible.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] This is not possible with type-I superconductors, since they cannot be penetrated by magnetic fields.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] If a superconductor is cooled in a field, the field can be trapped, which can allow the superconductor to be suspended over a magnet, with the potential for a frictionless joint or bearing.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] The worth of flux pinning is seen through many implementations such as lifts, frictionless joints, and transportation.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] The thinner the superconducting layer, the stronger the pinning that occurs when exposed to magnetic fields.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] Type-II superconductors are usually made of metal alloys or complex oxide ceramics.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] All high-temperature superconductors are type-II superconductors.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] While most elemental superconductors are type-I, niobium, vanadium, and technetium are elemental type-II superconductors.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] Boron-doped diamond and silicon are also type-II superconductors.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] Metal alloy superconductors can also exhibit type-II behavior (e.g., niobium–titanium, one of the most common superconductors in applied superconductivity), as well as intermetallic compounds like niobium–tin.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] Other type-II examples are the cuprate-perovskite ceramic materials which have achieved the highest superconducting critical temperatures.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] These include La1.85Ba0.15CuO4, BSCCO, and YBCO (Yttrium-Barium-Copper-Oxide), which is famous as the first material to achieve superconductivity above the boiling point of liquid nitrogen (77 K).
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] Due to strong vortex pinning, the cuprates are close to ideally hard superconductors.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] Strong superconducting electromagnets (used in MRI scanners, NMR machines, and particle accelerators) often use coils wound of niobium-titanium wires or, for higher fields, niobium-tin wires.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] These materials are type-II superconductors with substantial upper critical field *Hc2*, and in contrast to, for example, the cuprate superconductors with even higher *Hc2*, they can be easily machined into wires.
[src:superconducting-materials/type-ii-superconductor] Recently, however, 2nd generation superconducting tapes are allowing replacement of cheaper niobium-based wires with much more expensive, but superconductive at much higher temperatures and magnetic fields "2nd generation" tapes.
